The Chronicle Innocent Kurira, Sports Reporter
THE second leg of the Bulawayo Volleyball Association (BVA) premier league will take place at Milton High School from July 23-24. The two-day competition will see Highlanders, Lycans, Chimoio, Vipers and Spartans squaring off in the men’s category. In the ladies’ category, Chimoio, Vipers, Spartans and Lycans will do battle. <img class="wp-image-602143 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-39-3.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-39-3.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-39-3-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Covid-19 “We are having our league in a different format this time around. We are targeting at least four legs where at the end of the four competitions the points from all the meets will be tallied and we get a winner. “We are geared up for the second-leg and we expect to witness competitive action from all the teams,” said the BVA secretary-general Munyaradzi Chigudu.  Highlanders won all their four games in the first-leg played three weeks ago and collected 12 points in the process. Lycans were second with nine points. In the ladies’ category, Chimoio were also unbeaten, winning all their three games. <img class="wp-image-627517 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-34-10.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-34-10.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-34-10-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Milton High School During the Covid-19 enforced sporting break, BVA came up with var­i­ous projects meant to de­velop and improve the stan­dards of the game in the city and en­listed var­i­ous com­mit­tees into its struc­tures in a bid to make its brand more marketable and reach out to stake­hold­ers more ef­fec­tively. The enlisted committees are the ref­erees’ com­mis­sion, players’ commis­sion, mar­ket­ing com­mis­sion, gen­der com­mis­sion and coaches and corporate commis­sions. – @innocentskizoe